<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
        Mac App Store distribution rejects any executable inside the
        .app bundle that isn't App-Sandboxed. The main Scan target
        already opts in via Scan/Scan.entitlements; the Share Extension
        was missing its own entitlements file entirely and inherited
        nothing, so codesign shipped the .appex without
        com.apple.security.app-sandbox and App Store Connect rejected
        the upload with error 90296.

        On iOS the share extension is sandboxed implicitly and this
        key is ignored at runtime. On Mac Catalyst it's both required
        and enforced.

        The extension's runtime needs are intentionally narrow:

        • Input arrives via NSItemProvider on extensionContext — the
          OS marshals image/PDF data into the extension's address
          space outside the sandbox boundary, so no file or photos
          entitlement is required to read it.
        • Decoding is in-process via Vision / PDFKit — no network.
        • Hand-off to the host app uses the custom URL scheme
          me.nettrash.scan:// via the responder chain — Launch
          Services routes the open request and needs no entitlement.

        Therefore the only key we need is app-sandbox itself. Adding
        unused entitlements here would be flagged by App Review and
        broaden the attack surface for no benefit.
    -->
    <key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
